{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501767","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501767"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:33:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:33:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1788"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1788","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1788"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.21,0.16,0.18,0.37]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1788"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79371"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1788","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1788"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1788"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64693"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"655"},{"type":"tags","id":"2273"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"2572"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"3000"},{"type":"tags","id":"3583"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5868"},{"type":"tags","id":"6089"},{"type":"tags","id":"7178"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5493"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6455"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42402"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43103"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44869"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79371"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department following a four-metre fall from a roof. While falling, he attempted to grab the gutter with his right arm, causing sudden traction injury. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed. His pulse rate is 95/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His right hand demonstrates weakness of wrist and finger flexion. There is sensory loss along the medial forearm. His right eye shows ptosis and pupillary constriction compared to the left. The remainder of the neurological examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nerve root combinations is most likely affected?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["C4 and C5","C5 and C6","C6 and C7","C7 and C8","C8 and T1"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of Klumpke\u0027s palsy, a lower brachial plexus injury typically caused by forceful traction on an abducted arm. The combination of intrinsic hand muscle weakness, sensory loss along the medial forearm, and Horner\u0027s syndrome strongly suggests involvement of C8 and T1 nerve roots.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC8 and T1\u003C/strong\u003E nerve root injury produces weakness of intrinsic hand muscles and wrist flexors, with sensory loss along the medial forearm. T1 involvement specifically causes Horner\u0027s syndrome (ptosis, miosis, and anhydrosis) due to disruption of sympathetic fibres.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC4 and C5\u003C/strong\u003E involvement would primarily affect shoulder movement and present with deltoid weakness and sensory changes over the lateral upper arm, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC5 and C6\u003C/strong\u003E injury (Erb\u0027s palsy) typically presents with the characteristic \u0027waiter\u0027s tip\u0027 posture - arm internally rotated and adducted, extended elbow, and flexed wrist.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC6 and C7\u003C/strong\u003E involvement would cause weakness of elbow extension, wrist extension, and finger extension, with sensory changes over the lateral forearm and middle fingers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC7 and C8\u003C/strong\u003E injury would affect wrist and finger extension with sensory changes over the middle and ring fingers, but would not explain the Horner\u0027s syndrome seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Klumpke\u0027s palsy is a lower brachial plexus injury affecting C8-T1 nerve roots, typically caused by traction on an abducted arm","Classic features of Klumpke\u0027s palsy include weakness of intrinsic hand muscles, sensory loss along medial forearm, and Horner\u0027s syndrome","The presence of Horner\u0027s syndrome (ptosis, miosis, anhydrosis) specifically indicates T1 nerve root involvement"],"references":["Yoss R, Corbin K, McCarty C, Love J. Significance of symptoms and signs in localization of involved root in cervical disk protrusion. Neurology. 1957 Oct;7(10):673-83. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/13477342/","Carette S, Fehlings MG. Clinical practice. Cervical radiculopathy. N Engl J Med. 2005 Jul 28;353(4):392-9. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16049211/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64693"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1788"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64693","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64693"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T10:51:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T10:51:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1788"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79371"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"32","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/32"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurosurgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relati